The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by the Funix company Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a high-altitude province about New Jersey, home to 153 000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced gold and copper here for about $ 3.1 billion.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves, the cost of which is estimated at $ 78 billion.
These wealth, however, entails one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that the powerful armed forces of Indonesia retain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation by the New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands of greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this goldmine and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 papua and thousands have been raped, subjected to torture and imprisoned by Indonesian military forces since 1969.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killings in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the seventies can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – especially frequent, as stated in another report, rape and electric shock – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because the accidents take place every week,” says Andreas Harsono, who is researching in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts dragged on, as Papua’s resources attracted an influx of IDPs from other parts of Indonesia.
The 3.5 millionth population of the province is 83% Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants come from the densely populated Indonesian islands – Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan benches, "warungs", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "gadoo-yad", supplied with peanut sauce.
