According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, the soldiers who were drunk chased their children and beat them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus yemo, was so beaten that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government building of the election commission, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered in the football field in front of a local police station and a military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed ayta, a dance of the Papuan tribe mee pago: they ran in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and a military base.
When the situation was heated, the soldiers were ordered by internal radio communication: “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,” he said, according to an official document that correspondents of the magazine “TIME”, but which was not published in the local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Yeremias Kayama, the head of the district of Kugo Koto in Enorotal, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, appealing to the crowd with a request to go home.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayama still does not know who shot, but says that the bullet came from the side of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
In a local resident of Alfius Yowa got three times, as his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, tells him.
