“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and much more were injured.
News of the murders reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokovie made a ardent speech in Jayapur expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historical abuse of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be settled immediately, so that it never happens again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Viranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to end historical human rights violations.
But almost immediately went excuses.
“More than most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or at the beginning of the zero.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be done,” he said.
Then Viranto turned down his words, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to establish an organization to deal with Papua complaints.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through the trial.”
The Virantau, whom the United Nations accused of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the 1999 bloody vote for East Timor’s independence in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the incident in Paniai.
Families of victims from the Government met similar statements with a gloomy distrust.
“I’ve been asked four times in the last three years, but there has been absolutely no change,” Johannes says.
“I’m tired.”
He says he's still alive in fear years later.
“I’m scared,” he says.
