Italy is tightening its tone to ships of NGOs saving migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they would not be able to continue their work unless they obeyed the new rules governing their operations.
“If an NGO does not obey the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities,” Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with Turin’s daily Stampa newspaper.
Minniti’s warning came the day after Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rette on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which lasted only a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
