And what conclusion did you come to?
The Islamic State in Libya won not Haftar?
That's not what he did.
Haftar carried out operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And ISIS in Sirte fought the structures subordinated to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited people to Russia who carried out this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Regardie.
As we understand, you are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the mood of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, on the holding of the elections that Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Sarraj reached at the end of July in Paris?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, the agreements will be disrupted, the fighting will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Sarraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders spoke very negatively about each other.
As for Russia’s position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar on this day was on board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misrata, they did not believe in coincidence.
We were told: “You are probably very brave people who came to us today.”
But our task is precisely to show that we do not support Haftar only, we are conducting a dialogue with all the key parties to the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar talked.
Does mutual understanding with Russian partners on the human, emotional level make it easier that he studied twice in the USSR?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows, he is Russian.
But the fact that he studied here, of course, facilitates the dialogue with him.
And by the way, not just with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian well.
And are drawn to Russia, to some extent they experience nostalgia for it.
Do you consider it possible to cancel the arms embargo imposed on Libya?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
Of course, they are interested, but, as I said, we do not occupy someone in this conflict and would not like to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be in equal terms.
As for the arms embargo, the Libyans constantly make calls for Russia to somehow contribute to its removal.
The process of drafting a constitution is now being actively promoted in Libya.
We hope that the parties will come to compromise solutions, will achieve internal consensus.
Then the elections should be held, as discussed at the meeting of Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections are held and finally elected a legitimate government (and now neither of the parties has such a status), then it is possible to raise the issue of lifting the arms embargo in the UN Security Council.
Raising this issue is now meaningless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
The other day, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of floating from Libya African refugees, feels abandoned to the mercy of EU allies.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic is it for example that Haftar’s detachments will establish control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers who transport immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need the support of Russia, because Moscow is in dialogue with Haftar, and Sarraj, and Misurata and the south of the country.
And in this matter, a large role is played by tribes in southern Libya, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the southerners stop the flow of migrants on the far outwards?
That is, relatively speaking, turned back the buses in which Nigerian migrants go?
We're trying to do that.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in ensuring that these flows continue.
We hope to promote the unification of the southerners in the negotiation process between Sarraj, Haftar and tribes in the south.
But first we would like to see the unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Sarraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia law in the country.
How radical are he?
Will this not become an obstacle when building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself adheres to the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - a moderately Islamic, open to the world.
He is also actively fighting terrorists.
Where does he get that reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, there is the legislative, executive and judicial authorities.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in not climbing there.
And we mixed all the maps for them and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has concluded a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
Director of NOC Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft, Igor Sechin, concluded the deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft was carried out.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess I'm going to resell.
What are Russia’s economic interests in Libya?
Plans to re-sign the contracts concluded under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about the previous agreements in the transport sector (construction of railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do Libyans have anything to pay?
Well, they have oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, is the “oil in exchange for services” scheme?
I don’t know what the scheme will be, I don’t deal directly with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are actually working at peacemaking there.
For us, the main thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to agree among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya ceased to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task of helping the Libyan people and squeezing out terrorists from there.
Do you have any data on the presence of radical fighters from Russia or other countries of the former USSR in Libya (now or earlier)?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date, there is not a single native of Russia and other countries of the former USSR.
He said he had about 50 thousand. Recordings of telephone conversations of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "Kommersant") and the Russian speech does not sound there.
What kind of states are these fighters?
I wouldn't want to go into these details.
Let’s put it another way.
How many are the Libyans themselves among Islamist militants in Libya?
There are practically no Libyans among them, they are not more than 5%.
The others are strangers.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks on the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and declared their readiness to come to Moscow or to Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say right now.
Several visits should still take place, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of negotiations.
