Michel Carter's sentence for reports prompting Conrad Roy's suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for making text messages and phone calls to suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michel Carter, who is now 20, will have to serve 15 months of his term behind bars and another 5 years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said at a hearing on Thursday: “My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at large until the appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, squeezing her arms and lowering her eyes.
“By her actions, she killed Conrad Roy,” the prosecutor told the court.
“She interrupted his life to improve her.
She did not recognize responsibility,” she said.
“She didn’t show up remorse.”
But Carter’s lawyer said it was a “tragic case that she deeply regrets.”
However, Judge Lawrence Moniz said that, in his opinion, her “age, the level of maturity or even mental illness did not affect her actions in a noticeable way.”
The prosecutor read out the statements of Roy Lynn Roy, saying, “No day has passed when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I cope – I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever.
Roya's sister, Guamin, said that she was relentlessly persecuted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
“To be deprived of a man who has been with me always since I was born is the pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case appears to be a legal precedent, as Massachusetts does not have a law that would provide for responsibility for counseling to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The incident attracted the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter’s message.
“You can hang yourself, jump from the roof, I don’t know how many ways to stab yourself,” she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before the suicide, she wrote: "You have to do this, Conrad" and "You only need to turn on the ignition, and you will be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention through Roy’s death, and forbade her to communicate with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of lawyers were divided on this matter.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for the murder of her British apartmentmate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
30-year-old Knox published in the “Los Angeles Times” her dissenting opinion, which stated: “Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison.”
