“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he said.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
The Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Evidrian era and tells about the families who lived in the Cattle; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkevich, Bryoni May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabelle Greenberg.
This is not the first book of Rhodes, which is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "The Teeth of a Dead Man and Other Stories" - a collection of documents from the British Library; this project unexpectedly touched it to the depths of his soul.
“I could just touch the fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700’s by a double agent who worked for Jacobites,” he says.
"It's his fingerprint"
And the letters always smell of smoke, because in those days a fire was lit for lighting.
And in 300 years, in the future, you think you're there too.
How much I love the archives!”
For a man grasing with such a passion for old papers, to get support from the National Foundation and the English Art Council and live in the castle for four months (“Honestly, I have seen a little bit of a fortune,” it seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the "new" Victorian castle all day, walked the archives and considered numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that lay in the vomit of centuries.
He walked through the park and on the ruins of the old castle, talked with foresters, gardeners and sometimes with artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he “drinked whiskey and sat down to write.”
The history of Skotny Castle is not very studied, because the National Fund gained full access to it only in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassiy, died.
When Rhodes arrived there ten years later, employees were just beginning to deal with the archive, which he describes as “that the aristocrats have been dumping for the attic for centuries.”
Diaries, letters from the times of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think that the land disputes are boring," says Rhodes, " but this birch two families fought for this birch.
It happens, guys!”
In some of the stories of the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for broader research in English history: for example, in the "Worker", the hero leaves the castle just built to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
“There is a riot that occurred in the castle in 1380, in a book called the “Knightly families of Kent and Sussex,” says Rhodes.
“The peasant uprising began in these places, and I thought the riot was the right beginning.
Maybe they were connected?”
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, "Priest", which tells about the Jesuit priest, whom the Darrellov family hid at home for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Punisher", about the smuggler of the XVIII century Arthur Darrell, who is believed to stage his own funeral, punching stones (this was discovered a few years later, when the coffin was dug).
Darrels are a favorite family of Rhodes of all that were inhabited by the Cattle: “The gentlemen, it seems, were a perfect crook, forever got into debt and spent money on what they could not afford.
In different generations, Darrel men solved their problems with debts, marrying rich elderly women - I imagine them as a company of pretty guys who know how to care for the heirs of great states.
After finishing work at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Eliamyanmäki - the place where at the beginning of the 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it again overgrown with forest.
But the cattle remain a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he said.
“I felt something like this: damn it, I have to go back to real life again.”
Fifteen largest banks choose "Russia"
The conflict in the Association of Russian Banks (ARB) is developing: after Sberbank, VTB, VTB-24, Alfa-Bank, Gazprombank, Rosselkhozbank, Binbank and FC Otkritie, seven other credit institutions are going to leave this public organization.
Thus, the share of entities that have left ARB will account for at least 80 percent of the market.
But this is not just a way out - all the banks that announced the break with the ARB are negotiating with another public organization uniting credit institutions - the Association of Regional Banks "Russia", which is headed by a well-known politician Anatoly Aksakov, Chairman of the State Duma Committee on the Financial Market, recognized, by the way, following the results of the last session and the most effective head of the Duma committee and deputy in the number of draft laws prepared.
The beginning of the conflict within the ARB was laid during the discussion in the Federation Council, when the Interregional Banking Council considered new bills, in particular, involving a new classification of banks, depending on the size of the authorized capital.
Then Garegin Tosunyan, president of the ARB, said that, according to the association, this bill is adopted in the interests of the largest banks, which are thus trying to limit the capabilities of small and medium-sized banks in the regions, intercepting their clientele.
Among other claims there was also criticism of the Central Bank, which, according to Tosunyan, is not always justified to revoke licenses from some banks, which, however, was followed by the objection from the representative of the Central Bank: many heads of fined banks, in particular, Vneshprombank, were part of the governing bodies of the ARB.
Apparently, this exchange of mutually exclusive opinions in a very sensitive relationship with the main regulator of the banking environment and became a visible reason for the fifteen largest banks, declaring disagreement with the policy of the ARB, begin to prepare for the entry into the association "Russia", noting that "the effectiveness of the work of the ARB is at a low level, and a constructive dialogue within the banking community is not actually carried out."
Investors will be better
How's the case over?
We will answer immediately the main question that arises at the slightest failure or conflict in the banking sector or next to it: investors are not threatened, rather, on the contrary, the reliability of the banking system will increase.
Anatoly Aksakov, who is known for his scrupulousness in everything related to the interests of banks and their customers, a high-level professional who is highly valued in the Central Bank: almost all the leadership of the Central Bank is present at the annual events of the association, and all significant legislative initiatives of the regulator pass through expert assessments of the “regionals”.
In personnel and organizational terms, obviously, also, there are no special shocks.
Undoubtedly, the ARB gets into a difficult financial and managerial situation after they lose such powerful and influential participants with their contributions and lobbying opportunities.
However, in this oldest organization, an organization that defends the interests of the banking community, has considerable potential to continue to improve banking legislation and the sphere of monetary circulation in general.
It cannot be said that the association "Russia" with open arms is ready to accept on any conditions new members, judging by the reaction of its head, Anatoly Aksakov ("maybe too much will want"), who on July 21 at a briefing in the press center of the Parliamentary newspaper, said that "literally the next day, representatives of banks who left the ARB asked me to consider the possibility of increasing the potential of our association "Russia".
Their proposals are to strengthen the voice of bankers in the Association Council, as well as to pay more attention to new banking technologies.
Now the negotiation process is underway, the proposals of both sides are being studied, the agenda of the extraordinary congress of the association, which will be held in Sochi in mid-September as part of the international banking forum, is being prepared.
There we will decide.
Also, Anatoly Aksakov, stressing that "there is no such time as a chair", called the new head of the updated Association "Russia" Georgy Luntovsky, who leaves in September the post of Deputy Chairman of the Central Bank, highly describing his business and human qualities.
On August 18, Anatoly Aksakov, who is now resting in the Crimea, plans to interrupt his vacation for one day and arrive in Moscow, for an extraordinary meeting of the Council of the Association “Russia”, where it is planned to consider the issue of the agenda of the extraordinary Congress of “Russia”.
