Andrey Okhlopkov was transferred from the cosmodrome
As it became known to Kommersant, the technical director of the Vostochnyostsky cosmodrome, began to work at the Khrunichev State Space Research and Production Center (SCNPC).
Previously, he was de facto engaged in the construction of the Vostochny cosmodrome, but due to disagreements with the management of the Center for the Operation of Ground and Space Infrastructure (TSECI) was transferred to the enterprise in Moscow Fili, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. Okhlopkov will not be a replacement manager: the post of technical director will most likely be abolished, and the functionality is spread by the units of the TsENKI.
The fact that the technical director of the Eastern and the deputy general director of the TsENKI for technological development Andrey Okhlopkov moved to work in the Khrunichev SCNPC, Kommersant was told by top managers of several enterprises of the space industry, as well as an employee of the government apparatus.
"He has been working in a new post for several weeks," the interlocutors of Kommersant in the industry said.
It was not possible to get an operational comment from TsENKI on Thursday, and Mr. Okhlopkov himself was not available for comment.
However, the information "Kommersant" was officially confirmed in the SCNPC.
He decided to move to the position of director for the coordination of production, the company said. - Andrey Okhlopkov assigned to him the task of ensuring the starting minimum for the first launch at the Vostochny cosmodrome has fully fulfilled.
Mr. Okhlopkov moved to work in TsenKI in 2013, having service in the space forces, in particular on Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the "northern" cosmodrome, he held the post of first deputy commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrey Okhlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, with his filing, regional merchants received state orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill the obligations to clean the separated parts of the carrier rockets in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him innocent.
The responsibilities assigned to him in TSENKI for technological development extended to various projects, but the main of them was the construction of the cosmodrome in the Far East.
Oleg Ostapenko, who then headed the Federal Space Agency, in an interview with Kommersant, directly said that the situation on the East "was critical in October 2013."
The fact is that the planning was a strategic mistake: the completion of the construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were planned for the same time - the end of 2015.
To make a launch before the end of the year, they decided to complete the construction six months earlier and the deadlines were shifted from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, it was necessary to go to the trick: the specialists of the TsENKI began to conduct parallel installation of technological equipment at unfinished facilities.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrei Okhlopkov.
Despite the existing risks and still the postponement that occurred (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz flew away only on April 28, 2016), this idea justified itself, says a source of Kommersant at the cosmodrome: "Otherwise, we would not have carried out a single launch from the East, but would have been engaged in construction."
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his "space Susanin", but it was he who almost always asked for information about the progress of the construction site.
Mr. Okhlopkov was remembered for his directness: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroy) of the status of the only performer in the Eastern and directly work with subcontractors: "Why should we put all our eggs in one basket of Spetsstroy?"
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, CENKI has assumed the responsibilities of the general contractor to complete the construction and installation work on the starting and technical complex for the fourth quarter.
According to Kommersant, the reason for the transition of Mr. Okhlopkov to a new place of work was disagreements with the leadership of the TsNKI regarding how to complete the construction of structures and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as methods of working with subcontracting organizations.
“We decided that this would be better for everyone,” says one of the top managers involved in the construction of the East.
An employee of the government apparatus, in turn, calls the decision strange: "He was one of the best specialists, it will not be easy to find an equivalent replacement for him."
According to Kommersant, this will not be required: the position of technical director of the cosmodrome will be abolished, and its functions will be scattered to the units of the TsENKI.
