Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help relieve IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies have shown the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve symptoms in those who suffer from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate the symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of tryptophan protein contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the gut are making sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells that can trigger an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body and at the same time not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacterium in the intestines have increasing cell tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building elements of the protein - to start the appearance of these cells.
Professor Columna said: “We have established a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is part of the normal intestinal microbiome, and the development of a population of tolerance-intensive cells.
The more tryptophan was contained in the nutrition of mice, the more these immune cells they had.
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan may contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation of the environment in the intestine.
Postdoc Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barganvas, studying a type of tolerance-intensifying immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separately, they were not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the intestinal microbiomes of mice – communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestinium cells of the mice was sequenced, and six species of bacteria present in mice with immune cells were found, but not in mice that do not have them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reutri, and their immune cells appeared.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then suffered small portions of fluid – without bacteria – to undefeated immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have turned into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan, known as indole-3-milk acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the food of mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophane level was halved, the number of cells also doubled.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragagan explains that people have the same tolerance-in-tolerance cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether triptophan byproducts from L. reuteri develop cells in humans as well as mice, but people with inflammatory bowel disease have been found to have defects in the genes associated with tryptophan.
She says: "Perhaps the development of these cells should be strengthened by us, since inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reutri could potentially lead to expansion of their population.
