White House Requisite Costs Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
According to the military records provided by TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to drive a Marine helicopter to the Southern Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as 24 000 dollars.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the "Marine One", when the board is the president, became the central element of the event held on July 17 at the White House, which demonstrated American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and White House top officials inspected technology products from all fifty states.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was exhibited next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the Marine Corps First Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for the control of the helicopter, the White House Military Directorate ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South lawn on the occasion of the “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to make sure you know you’re aware because it’s an unusual widely public event in the press,” the commander of HMX-1 wrote in an email to his boss, first deputy chief of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the shipment from the White House is delayed, a second crew will need a second crew for a return flight in accordance with restrictions on opening hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the security officers of the unit remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by TIME magazine, it remained unclear whether the second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch law prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 specified whether the event contradicts this resolution.
“Among other things, we asked if this is a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told that it is not,” the commander wrote.
“It looks like you have nowhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The “Made in America” event was declared by the White House as an official event, and Hatch’s law was not covered.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to promote health care reform at that time in the development of the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is unlikely to be a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But to ask for them is the only one in the interests of the photo possibility is unusual.
Trump was already discussed in February when the presidential plane hit the back track during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was littered with messages with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’s show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House spokeswoman Lindsey Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the transportation of the President of the United States to the White House with an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 held 58 training landings outside the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the event “Made in America” was counted on the crew in the account of the necessary training flights for the month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours on that day as part of “non-presidential support tasks.”
According to the White House, taxpayers were not spent on the cost of any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company did not take part in the organization of a helicopter demonstration on the South lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep a budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Ministry of Defense’s hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the defense defense reimbursement rate for VH-3D is 24,380 US dollars per hour of flight.
The recordings of the unit recorded that the airborne time was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield at the Quantico Marine Corps in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this bet.
“Calking the cost for taxpayers, based on the exemplary rate of compensation, is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These approximate rates include personnel, service, and many other irreversible costs that are included in annual allocations.”
According to a 2015 study by RAND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do not take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and the costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in defense of using a helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to showcase the things done in America this week,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I assume, if not a thousand people, whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, which has worked tirelessly so many Americans.
Therefore, of course, it is appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter, inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely slept in a driver’s seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump appealed to representatives of the company “Sikorsky”, joking with the press on the topic of his own fleet of products of the company.
“I know Sikorsky well,” the president said. I have three of them.”
